I just have to jump in on this discussion.  Pine is fantastic.  It has
been a lifesaver in teaching newcomers how to use email.  I started out
last year with unix mail and it was so hard for me, who had never used
computers at all.  Pine was so much simpler, and yes, it is for naive
newbies.  

This year I have helped many new teachers and students on internet
learn to use pine.  It is a wonderful program.

Specifically, as several others have pointed out, it asks you
if you want to post to the newsgroup.  That is pretty plain for
even the most naive.  But just in case it's not, pine also warns
you, "posted message may go to thousands of readers.  post it?"
Surely anyone, if not sure what that means, would say no, if not
intending to send it to thousands of folks....

It seems to me, that you have been embarrassed by someone's "accidental"
post to a newsgroup (maybe it was intentional?)....and are taking it
out on the makers of pine.  Something new users around here are
often warned about is that email is NOT totally private.  Once you
send something, it may end up anywhere, and you should consider
that when you send it.

I not only love pine, but I love this newsgroup, because up until
this thread, it has been one of the most pleasant flame-free
newsgroups I have had a chance to read.





