In article <3kq7o8$o02@gaia.ucs.orst.edu>,
John Stanley <stanley@skyking.OCE.ORST.EDU> wrote:
>In article <19950317161032.olly@mantis.co.uk>,
>Olly Betts <olly@mantis.co.uk> wrote:
>>So I could easily reference future messages if I actually wanted to.  I
>>could send a large message in several chunks, such that each message
>>references all the others.
>
>So could you in news. If you want to create your own, you can make them
>link however you want.

Indeed.  However, if it's mail, this is perfectly valid by RFC822.  In news,
RFC1036 describes exactly how to create the references line, and this would
be invalid.  You could do it, of course, but you shouldn't.

I was pointing out that your original assertion:

>... it is impossible for a mail references header to contain the
>ids of messages that aren't older than the mail the header is in.

is incorrect.  Not only is it possible, but it's valid.  However, if the
references line in news is constructed as RFC1036 says, then the messages
referenced must be older, and further must be ancestors of the current
article.  Neither of these is true of RFC822 references in mail.

Olly
